===Etymology===
[[Image:Capreolus capreolus (Marek Szczepanek).jpg|thumb|A roe deer]]
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|rāhdēor||roe deer}}, corresponding to {{term|roe}} + {{term|deer}}. Cognate with Icelandic {{term|rádýr|lang=is}}, Swedish {{term|rådjur|lang=sv}}, Danish {{term|rådyr|lang=da}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈɹəʊˌdɪə/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-uk-roe deer.ogg|Audio (UK)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|head=[[roe]] [[deer]]|roe deer}}

# A small, [[nimble]] [[Eurasian]] [[deer]] with short three-pointed [[antlers]], no visible [[tail]], a white [[rump]] patch, and a reddish [[summer]] [[coat]] that turns [[grey]] in [[winter]] ({{taxlink|Capreolus capreolus|species|noshow=1}}).
#* '''1955''', {{w|Robin Jenkins}}, ''The Cone-Gatherers'', Canongate 2012, page 84:
#*: Frightened by the noises approaching them from the rear, and and apprehensive of the human silence ahead, the five '''roe deer''' were halted, their heads high in nervous alertness.

